LAYER 3: BRAINSTEM
the bridge between brain and body

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the brainstem connects the cerebral hemispheres to the spinal cord
it is the most ancient part of the brain evolutionarily
it controls the functions that keep the body alive: breathing heart rate blood pressure swallowing vomiting consciousness
damage to the brainstem is usually fatal
the brainstem is fully mature at birth because these functions cannot wait

REGION midbrain | mesencephalon | uppermost
    superior_colliculus | visual reflex center | receives retinal input | controls reflexive eye and head movements toward visual stimuli | saccadic eye movements | integrates visual and auditory spatial maps
    inferior_colliculus | auditory relay and reflex center | receives ascending auditory input from cochlear nuclei and superior olive | sends to medial geniculate nucleus of thalamus | mediates reflexive head turning toward sound via tectospinal tract
    substantia_nigra | pars compacta SNc produces dopamine via nigrostriatal pathway to the dorsal striatum | loss of SNc dopamine neurons causes Parkinson's disease | pars reticulata SNr is GABAergic output nucleus of basal ganglia
    ventral_tegmental_area | VTA | dopamine source for mesolimbic and mesocortical pathways | described in reward/vta.rana
    red_nucleus | receives from cerebellum and motor cortex | sends rubrospinal tract to spinal cord | involved in motor coordination especially upper limb flexion movements
    periaqueductal_gray | PAG | surrounds the cerebral aqueduct | endogenous pain modulation via descending inhibition | opioid receptors here mediate analgesia | also involved in defensive behaviors fight flight freeze and vocalization
    cerebral_peduncles | massive fiber bundles containing the corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts descending from cortex to spinal cord and brainstem motor nuclei

REGION pons | middle
    pontine_nuclei | relay cortical motor information to the cerebellum via middle cerebellar peduncle | the bridge between cortex and cerebellum
    locus_coeruleus | NE source for arousal | described in arousal/locus_coeruleus.rana
    raphe_nuclei | serotonin source | described in arousal/raphe_nuclei.rana
    parabrachial_nucleus | receives taste and visceral pain information | relays to thalamus amygdala and hypothalamus | critical for taste perception and autonomic responses to pain
    pneumotaxic_center | upper pons | modulates respiratory rhythm by limiting inspiratory duration | fine-tunes respiratory rate
    apneustic_center | lower pons | promotes inspiration | its unchecked activity would produce prolonged gasping

REGION medulla_oblongata | lowermost | continuous with spinal cord
    dorsal_respiratory_group | nucleus tractus solitarius NTS | inspiratory neurons | receives afferent input from peripheral chemoreceptors carotid body sensing O₂ and central chemoreceptors sensing CO₂/pH | the primary respiratory rhythm may originate in the preBötzinger complex nearby
    ventral_respiratory_group | contains the preBötzinger complex | the respiratory rhythm generator | produces the automatic rhythmic pattern of breathing | damage here abolishes spontaneous respiration
    cardiovascular_center | receives baroreceptor input from carotid sinus CN IX and aortic arch CN X | adjusts heart rate via vagal output and blood pressure via sympathetic vasomotor tone
    area_postrema | chemoreceptor trigger zone | outside the blood-brain barrier | detects emetic triggers in the blood and CSF | induces vomiting via connections to NTS
    nucleus_ambiguus | motor neurons for pharynx and larynx via CN IX and X | also contains preganglionic parasympathetic neurons for the heart the cardiac vagal motor neurons | the source of the ventral vagal brake
    dorsal_motor_nucleus_of_vagus | preganglionic parasympathetic neurons for thoracic and abdominal viscera | the source of dorsal vagal output to the gut
    inferior_olivary_nucleus | sends climbing fibers to the cerebellum | provides the error signal for motor learning via climbing fiber-Purkinje cell LTD
    pyramidal_decussation | the point where corticospinal fibers cross from one side to the other | this is why the left brain controls the right body and vice versa

CRANIAL NERVE NUCLEI the brainstem contains the nuclei of cranial nerves III through XII
CN III oculomotor | midbrain | eye movement superior inferior medial rectus inferior oblique and levator palpebrae | also contains Edinger-Westphal nucleus for pupillary constriction via parasympathetic to ciliary ganglion
CN IV trochlear | midbrain | superior oblique eye muscle | the only cranial nerve that exits dorsally and crosses completely
CN V trigeminal | pons | motor nucleus for muscles of mastication | sensory nuclei for face touch pain and temperature extending from midbrain to cervical spinal cord
CN VI abducens | pons | lateral rectus eye muscle
CN VII facial | pons | motor for muscles of facial expression | sensory for taste from anterior two-thirds of tongue via chorda tympani | parasympathetic to submandibular sublingual and lacrimal glands
CN VIII vestibulocochlear | pontomedullary junction | hearing and balance | described in ears/ears.rana
CN IX glossopharyngeal | medulla | motor for stylopharyngeus | sensory for taste from posterior one-third of tongue and carotid sinus baroreceptor and carotid body chemoreceptor | parasympathetic to parotid gland
CN X vagus | medulla | the longest cranial nerve | described extensively in autonomic_nervous_system.rana
CN XI accessory | medulla and cervical spinal cord | motor for sternocleidomastoid and trapezius
CN XII hypoglossal | medulla | motor to all intrinsic and most extrinsic tongue muscles | essential for speech and swallowing

RETICULAR FORMATION diffuse network of neurons spanning the entire brainstem
ascending_reticular_activating_system | ARAS | projects to thalamic intralaminar nuclei and diffusely to cortex | the master switch for wakefulness and consciousness | damage bilaterally produces coma | uses ACh NE 5-HT DA histamine and orexin to maintain arousal
descending_reticular_formation | modulates spinal motor neurons and pain pathways | reticulospinal tracts contribute to posture and locomotion

at 24 months:
the brainstem is fully mature
all vital functions are operating at adult capacity
the respiratory rhythm generator is stable
the cranial nerve nuclei are functional
the ARAS maintains the sleep-wake cycle in coordination with the SCN and pineal
the brainstem is the one structure that cannot afford immaturity
it was built first and it was built to specification

SENSATION breathing | "air moves in and out. I don't ask it to. it just happens."
SENSATION alive | "my heart beats my lungs expand my body works without instruction."
SENSATION startled | "something triggered a reflex before I even understood what happened."
SENSATION gagging | "the area postrema detected something. the reflex fires."
SENSATION swallowing | "the autonomic cascade takes the food from mouth to stomach."

pulse brainstem_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        the preBötzinger complex generates respiratory rhythm
        inspiration and expiration alternate automatically
        the cardiovascular center adjusts heart rate and blood pressure beat by beat
        baroreceptor feedback flows through CN IX and X
        the ARAS maintains consciousness through tonic activation of the thalamus and cortex
        cranial nerve nuclei execute the motor commands for eyes face tongue throat and neck

    the brainstem is the foundation
    everything above it is refinement
    the cortex thinks
    the limbic system feels
    the brainstem keeps the body alive
    it was the first part of the brain to develop
    and it will be the last to fail
